    <h3>Grammar</h3>
    <br>
    <span>B. Complete each sentence using what/how/where/whether + one of these verbs:</span>
    <br>
    <br>
    a. Do you know <b><u>how to get</u></b> to Rama&rsquo;s house?
    <br>
    <br>
    b. I don&rsquo;t know <b><u>whether to apply</u></b> for the job or not.
    <br>
    <br>
    c. Have you decided <b><u>where to go</u></b> for your picnic?
    <br>
    <br>
    d. Can you show me <b><u>how to use</u></b> this camera?
    <br>
    <br>
    e. Ask Hari. He&rsquo;ll tell you <b><u>how to ride</u></b> a bicycle.
    <br>
    <br>
    f. I was really astonished. I didn&rsquo;t know <b><u>how to ride</u></b> on the horse.
    <br>
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>C. Paraphrase the following sentences using the verb in brackets as in the example.</span>
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>a. Mahesh forgets to close the windows. (tend)</span>
    <br>
    Mahesh tends to forget closing the windows
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>b. Your car has broken down. (appear)</span>
    <br>
    Your car appears to have broken down.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>c. Ashika is worried about her exam. (seem)</span>
    <br>
    Ashika seems to be worried about her exam.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>d. They have developed the theory. (claim)</span>
    <br>
    They claim to have developed the theory.
    <br>
    <br>
    <span>e. He&rsquo;s enjoying his new job. (pretend)</span>
    <br>
    He pretends to be enjoying his new job.
